('I-33383', 'Configure telemetry data set and frequency of receiving data set [Release 2.2.1]', 'Title: Configure telemetry data set and frequency of receiving data set [Release 2.2.1]


Goal:
To see and configure what data will be included in the required basic and full sets of received telemetry data to have the information carsharing operator need and to ensure optimal operating conditions.


Actors:
Human: Fleet owner/manager/operator
System: Atom telematics system, third party carsharing operator''s FMS


Scope:
Atom telematics system, third party carsharing operator''s FMS, Cloud, Fleet API


Context : 
Fleet owner/manager/operator should be able to set the frequency of receiving frames with data in the telematics settings, select the data he wants to receive in general and in each frame (packet). :


Preconditions:
The connection parameters are configured, the user can receive telemetry data. The vehicle has an active Internet connection. Trigger: The user navigates to the vehicle/group of vehicles setup service via in_82 third party FMS.


Main Scenario:
1. The FMS gets the current telemetry data set configuration for the vehicle/group of vehicles from Cloud.
2. The FMS configures the list of available basic telemetry data to be received:
for the vehicle turned on with the default period of 1 s for periodic signals and by trigger for state signals. for the vehicle turned off with the default period of 900 s for periodic signals. 3. Fleet owner/manager/operator selects/unselects telemetry data from the configured list via in_82 third party FMS for the vehicle turned on/off.
4. Fleet owner/manager/operator configures groups from selected telemetry signals to receive telemetry data grouped into one telemetry packets/frames via in_82 third party FMS.
5. Fleet owner/manager/operator specifies the frequency of receiving for each telemetry signal/group of signals within range from 1 s to 65535 s via in_82 third party FMS.
6. Fleet owner/manager/operator sets up triggers (via in_82 third party FMS) to receive each telemetry signal/group of signals specifying one of the following:
By changing the value of one or more signals from the list of available basic telemetry data; By selecting the delta (change threshold) of one or more signals; By reaching a certain value of one or more signals. 7. Fleet owner/manager/operator applies the created settings to the vehicle/group of vehicles via in_82 third party FMS.


Postconditions:
Configured sets, triggers, data acquisition schedules are applied to the vehicle/group of vehicles. Fleet owner/manager/operator receives telemetry data in accordance with the created settings. Requirements:
For each group of signals Fleet owner/manager/operator can set up triggers only based on the the signals included in this group of signals. Fleet owner/manager/operator should be able to analyze the settings via out_82 third party FMS. For each parameter, it should be possible to set one or more transmission types for turned on and turned off vehicle modes. Fleet owner/manager/operator must be able to receive telemetry data grouped into telemetry packets/frames, but not each parameter individually. In this case, it should be possible to send data asynchronously in a separate frame. The FMS should allow selection of only telemetry data available for the relevant vehicle states: "Vehicle is turned-on": the state when (or):
The vehicle is booked, In user inspection mode, but with the engine blocked, when the vehicle is rented (standing still or moving). "Vehicle is turned-off": state when the vehicle is parked, closed and not in use (not for rent). In this state the vehicle consumes a minimum of energy, but it has the ability to send required basic telemetry data set, statuses of security systems in case their activation (perimeter violation).', '[Touchpoint-978170] Touchpoints / 82. third party FMS (Draft)', '[Touchpoint-978170] Touchpoints / 82. third party FMS (Draft)', '[ECOSYSTEM.PD_Soft - 1160746] Ecosystem product definition /  Configuration tool (Ready for development)', ''),
('I-33384', 'Receive a set of telemetry data from the vehicle turned on (B2B) [Release 2.2.1]', 'Title:
Receive a set of telemetry data from the vehicle turned on (B2B) (Release 2.2.1)


Goal:
Fleet owner/manager/operator obtains the telemetry data available when the vehicle is turn on to analyze the status of the vehicle, and how well Carsharing Driver controls it.


Scope:
Third party carsharing operator''s FMS, Atom telematics system, Fleet API
Context:
The vehicle systems in turned-on state (see requirements) are running and their current status can be sent as part of telemetry data. When entering this state, the carsharing operator must receive all current data about the state of the vehicle and its systems. In this state, data with a possible high frequency of sending is sent when it changes.


